The [[Sweden|Swedish]] national legislature, [[Riksdag_of_the_Estates|since medieval times]], has borne a different style, [[Riksdag|Riksdag]], which is cognate to the old name of the German national assembly, [[Reichstag_(building)|Reichstag]]. In Sweden ''ting'' is however used to name the subnational county councils, which are called [[County_Councils_of_Sweden|Landsting]]. That name was also used in medieval times for the tings that governed the historical [[Provinces_of_Sweden|Landskap]] provinces, that were superseded by the [[Counties_of_Sweden|counties]] in the 17th century. The name ''ting'' is also found in the names of the first level instances of the Swedish and Finnish [[court|court]] system, which are called [[tingsrätt|tingsrätt]] ({{lang-fi|käräjäoikeus}}), the Court of the Thing.

Similarly, prior to 1953, the [[Denmark|Danish]] legislature was known as [[Rigsdagen|Rigsdagen]], which comprised the two houses of the [[Folketinget|Folketinget]] (People's Thing) and [[Landstinget|Landstinget]] (The Land Thing). The latter, which was reserved for people of means, was abolished by the constitution of 1953.

[[Swedish_Assembly_of_Finland|Folkting]] is also the name of the Swedish Assembly of Finland, a semi-official body representing the [[Finland-Swedish|Swedish-speaking population]] (''Svenskfinland'' or "Swedish Finland").

In addition, there are three distinct elected [[Sami_people|Sami]] assemblies that are all called [[Sametinget|Sameting]] in Norwegian and Swedish.

The Norwegian parliament, the Storting, has historically been divided into two [[Bicameralism|chambers]] named the Lagting and the Odelsting, which translates loosely into the Thing of the Law and the Thing of the Lords. However, for much of the Storting's recent history, the division into Lagting and Odelsting has been mostly ceremonial, and the Storting has generally operated as a [[unicameralism|unicameral]] parliament. A constitutional amendment passed in February 2007 abolished the Lagting and Odelsting, making this ''de facto'' unicameralism official following the [[Norwegian_parliamentary_election,_2009|2009 election]].

